<item>
 <title>Meet Fellows for Peace Alumni</title>
 <link>https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/fellows/-complete-list-of-2013-fellows-/meet-fellows-for-peace-alumni/node/436</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Established in 2007 by the late Kathryn Wasserman Davis, the Fellows for Peace program challenges Middlebury College and the Monterey Institute of International Studies to use their combined expertise in language acquisition and policy studies to recruit and train peacemakers. In the pages that follow, we explore the impact of the program by investigating the work of current and former Kathryn Davis Fellows. Meet a selected few alumni below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/joe_hillips.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Joseph Phillips&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the very first Kathryn Davis Fellows for Peace, Joseph Phillips came to Middlebury directly from Moscow, where he was an attaché in the Arms Control Implementation Unit of the U.S. Army. He now teaches Russian to the next generation of soldiers at the Defense Language Institute Foreign Language Center in Monterey, California.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/helene-songe_0.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Helene Songe &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In 2010, Helene Songe had been working at the United Nations Relief and Works Agency in Damascus, Syria, for over a year. A summer as a Kathryn Davis Fellow in the Middlebury Arabic School allowed her to better understand the Palestinian refugee population she was serving. Forced to leave Syria by escalating unrest, Helene is now working for the United Nations Relief and Works Agency in Colombia. She hopes to return soon to the Middle East.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/rana-abdul-aziz_0.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rana Abdul-Aziz Rana &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Abdul-Aziz’s passion for education helped her earn a Kathryn Davis Fellowship in the School of Hebrew five years ago. The experience of going back to the beginning as a language learner profoundly influenced her own pedagogy. Rana is now the Arabic language coordinator at Tufts University, giving courses to undergraduates and training fellow instructors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/catherine-stanley_0.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Catherine Stanley &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Catherine Stanley came to Middlebury as a 2011 Kathryn Davis Fellow to more successfully advocate with Russianspeaking authorities on behalf of underserved children. After 12 years working in Kazakhstan to improve conditions and prospects for orphans, Catherine recently moved to the Operation Mercy headquarters in Sweden. There she will manage international projects and develop the nongovernmental organization’s humanitarian relief capacity before eventually returning to the field in Central Asia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/nikita-perfilyev_0.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nikita Perfilyev &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A Fulbright Fellowship brought Nikita Perfilyev from Russia to the Monterey Institute, where he continued his advanced studies in nonproliferation and Chinese language. In 2009, a Kathryn Davis Fellowship helped him add linguistic and cultural expertise to his arsenal of skills. Now working on outreach and education at the Preparatory Commission for the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, Nikita has dedicated his life to nonproliferation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img title=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://www.davisfellowsforpeace.org/system/files/christa-bryant_0.jpg&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Christa Bryant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the summer of 2012, Christa was a seasoned journalist, but a beginner in Hebrew. Christa now lives and works among native speakers of Hebrew, as the Jerusalem bureau chief for the Christian Science Monitor. Not a day goes by when she does not use what she learned as a Kathryn Davis Fellow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
